    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Is Alcohol the Culprit in Violence?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Harvey Weiner letter hails Caroline Knapp's June 21 article; holds alcohol is drug that causes most crime and violence in American and should be included in drug prevention programs</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Bravo to Caroline Knapp for highlighting the role of alcohol in the violence in Central Park and in Los Angeles (Op-Ed, June 21). Although alcohol is the drug that causes the most crime and violence in America each year, government officials responsible for the war on drugs don't include alcohol in prevention messages aimed at youth. Whither common sense?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Bravo to Caroline Knapp for highlighting the role of alcohol in the violence in Central Park and in Los Angeles (Op-Ed, June 21). Although alcohol is the drug that causes the most crime and violence in America each year, government officials responsible for the war on drugs don't include alcohol in prevention messages aimed at youth. Whither common sense?</p>
        <p>Also, why are alcoholic beverages excluded from government regulations that require content labels on all bottled and canned beverages sold in the United States?</p>
        <p>HARVEY WEINER  Wynnewood, Pa., June 21, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is vice president for health affairs, Eagleville Hospital.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
